<dl id="un1005p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1005">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1005p"> (NLI.3) 5(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Shelley (Mrs): Frankenstein</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> <mark>Mrs. Percy Shelley</mark>, as befitted the widow of so great a magician of language, reached a purer style and a more impressive imagination in her ghastly romance of <mark><cite>Frankenstein</cite></mark>, which has given an image (usually misquoted) to everyday English speech, and may still be read with genuine terror and pity. <small> Edmund Gosse, <a name="EGSH" href="/udra/udex.htm#EGSH"><cite title="source">A Short History of Modern English Literature</cite></a> (1897), 327f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley (1797-1851). </mm> </dd></dl>
